1
00:00:00,150 --> 00:00:02,779
- This video is sponsored by CuriosityStream and Nebula.

2
00:00:02,930 --> 00:00:04,839
If you wanna become a more disciplined person

3
00:00:04,839 --> 00:00:07,386
the key to doing that is in this book,

4
00:00:07,386 --> 00:00:09,289
"The Power of Habit" by Charles Duhigg,

5
00:00:09,289 --> 00:00:12,829
specifically in chapter five on page 142.

6
00:00:12,830 --> 00:00:15,160
Now you might be thinking the answer is building habits,

7
00:00:15,160 --> 00:00:16,450
but that's not it,

8
00:00:16,449 --> 00:00:18,598
it's something different and it's hidden in plain sight

9
00:00:18,600 --> 00:00:21,080
in one of the studies that he talks about in this book.

10
00:00:21,079 --> 00:00:22,488
So back in the early 90s,

11
00:00:22,489 --> 00:00:24,439
just one year after I was born,

12
00:00:24,440 --> 00:00:26,910
a psychologist went to a hospital in Scotland

13
00:00:26,910 --> 00:00:28,850
and did a study involving patients

14
00:00:28,850 --> 00:00:30,479
of knee replacement surgeries.

15
00:00:30,480 --> 00:00:32,359
Now, if you know anything about this type of surgery,

16
00:00:32,359 --> 00:00:34,629
you will know that movement and physical rehabilitation

17
00:00:34,630 --> 00:00:37,710
is crucial almost immediately after the surgery is done

18
00:00:37,710 --> 00:00:40,100
if the patient is going to fully recover their mobility.

19
00:00:40,100 --> 00:00:41,340
But there's a problem,

20
00:00:41,340 --> 00:00:43,960
moving after a knee replacement is agonizing,

21
00:00:43,960 --> 00:00:45,550
it's incredibly painful.

22
00:00:45,549 --> 00:00:46,382
And for that reason,

23
00:00:46,383 --> 00:00:48,260
a lot of people who get this type of surgery

24
00:00:48,259 --> 00:00:49,688
never fully recover.

25
00:00:49,689 --> 00:00:51,749
So the psychologist took about 60 of these patients

26
00:00:51,750 --> 00:00:55,450
and had them write down specific detailed plans on paper

27
00:00:55,450 --> 00:00:57,290
of how they were going to go about their recovery.

28
00:00:57,289 --> 00:00:58,639
And something remarkable happened.

29
00:00:58,640 --> 00:01:00,220
The patients who actually wrote down a plan

30
00:01:00,219 --> 00:01:01,319
for what they were going to do

31
00:01:01,320 --> 00:01:02,949
are much more likely to do it

32
00:01:02,950 --> 00:01:04,950
and push through the pain when it came.

33
00:01:04,950 --> 00:01:06,890
And my favorite example was a man who committed

34
00:01:06,890 --> 00:01:08,730
to walking to the bus stop every day

35
00:01:08,730 --> 00:01:11,310
to meet his wife as she came home from work.

36
00:01:11,310 --> 00:01:14,030
And that right there is the key to self-discipline.

37
00:01:14,030 --> 00:01:16,079
It's hidden in plain sight in that example,

38
00:01:16,079 --> 00:01:18,108
and in interactions that we have with people

39
00:01:18,109 --> 00:01:19,409
every single day.

40
00:01:19,409 --> 00:01:21,808
The key is accountability,

41
00:01:21,810 --> 00:01:22,999
you could also call it duty,

42
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:25,250
the obligations we have to each other.

43
00:01:25,250 --> 00:01:27,430
When your boss tells you to be to work at a specific time,

44
00:01:27,430 --> 00:01:28,920
you are there at a specific time

45
00:01:28,920 --> 00:01:31,230
because your boss is relying on you.

46
00:01:31,230 --> 00:01:32,280
When your little brother asks you

47
00:01:32,280 --> 00:01:33,390
to pick them up from school,

48
00:01:33,390 --> 00:01:35,240
you do it because he is relying on you.

49
00:01:35,239 --> 00:01:36,908
But what about our personal goals?

50
00:01:36,909 --> 00:01:38,969
What about that instrument you've been meaning to learn

51
00:01:38,969 --> 00:01:41,178
or the workout routine you're trying to stick to?

52
00:01:41,180 --> 00:01:42,660
With these personal goals,

53
00:01:42,659 --> 00:01:44,668
there's nobody else really relying on us.

54
00:01:44,670 --> 00:01:46,899
So we can't really tap accountability

55
00:01:46,900 --> 00:01:49,540
to improve our self-discipline, can we?

56
00:01:49,540 --> 00:01:50,560
Well, actually we can.

57
00:01:50,560 --> 00:01:51,393
And in this video,

58
00:01:51,393 --> 00:01:53,010
we're going to explore a model that I'm calling

59
00:01:53,010 --> 00:01:55,030
the five levels of self-discipline.

60
00:01:55,030 --> 00:01:57,789
Each levels in this model has to do with a different type

61
00:01:57,790 --> 00:02:01,229
of accountability that can be applied to augment and improve

62
00:02:01,230 --> 00:02:02,530
your levels of self-discipline.

63
00:02:02,530 --> 00:02:03,719
Four levels in this model

64
00:02:03,719 --> 00:02:05,779
have to do with our relationships to other people.

65
00:02:05,780 --> 00:02:07,300
And they are the most powerful levels,

66
00:02:07,299 --> 00:02:09,689
but the first one is worth mentioning as well.

67
00:02:09,689 --> 00:02:12,349
And that is accountability to yourself.

68
00:02:12,349 --> 00:02:14,639
Now, as the first level, this is the weakest one,

69
00:02:14,639 --> 00:02:18,248
but it is not weak per se can actually be very powerful

70
00:02:18,250 --> 00:02:21,640
and the study in this book is proof of that.

71
00:02:21,639 --> 00:02:23,688
Now, the man who chose to meet his wife at the bus stop

72
00:02:23,689 --> 00:02:26,358
is my favorite example because he involved another person

73
00:02:26,360 --> 00:02:27,193
in the equation.

74
00:02:27,193 --> 00:02:29,240
But everyone else who was successful in this study

75
00:02:29,240 --> 00:02:31,639
didn't have anybody else that was really relying on them

76
00:02:31,639 --> 00:02:32,629
yet they were successful

77
00:02:32,629 --> 00:02:35,499
because they held themselves accountable.

78
00:02:35,500 --> 00:02:38,180
They made plans and then stuck to them later on.

79
00:02:38,180 --> 00:02:39,569
Every time we make a plan,

80
00:02:39,569 --> 00:02:41,468
every time we sit down and write out a task

81
00:02:41,469 --> 00:02:44,239
or add something to our calendar or decide to do something,

82
00:02:44,240 --> 00:02:46,389
we are essentially trying to hold

83
00:02:46,389 --> 00:02:48,478
our future selves accountable.

84
00:02:48,479 --> 00:02:50,528
And the study here illustrates

85
00:02:50,530 --> 00:02:52,539
how to be more successful with that.

86
00:02:52,539 --> 00:02:54,309
Number one, make it tangible,

87
00:02:54,310 --> 00:02:55,680
write down what you're going to do,

88
00:02:55,680 --> 00:02:58,220
and number two, be specific about it.

89
00:02:58,219 --> 00:03:00,089
Write down exactly what you were going to do

90
00:03:00,090 --> 00:03:02,580
and what conditions may cause you to fail.

91
00:03:02,580 --> 00:03:03,910
This last part is also echoed

92
00:03:03,909 --> 00:03:05,989
in Seth Godin's excellent book, "The Dip".

93
00:03:05,990 --> 00:03:08,099
When he talks about how marathoners often decide

94
00:03:08,099 --> 00:03:11,438
what will cause them to quit before they start the race.

95
00:03:11,439 --> 00:03:12,989
That way they are pre-committing

96
00:03:12,990 --> 00:03:15,179
to the conditions that would cause them to drop out,

97
00:03:15,180 --> 00:03:17,749
and when the discomfort hits later on in the marathon,

98
00:03:17,750 --> 00:03:20,100
maybe 18 or 19 miles in they'll know,

99
00:03:20,099 --> 00:03:22,929
I committed to other conditions that would make me quit

100
00:03:22,930 --> 00:03:25,530
this is not one of them therefore I'm going to push through.

101
00:03:25,530 --> 00:03:27,060
Level two is the first level

102
00:03:27,060 --> 00:03:29,649
where we introduce relationships to other people

103
00:03:29,650 --> 00:03:30,700
and in doing so,

104
00:03:30,699 --> 00:03:33,308
the accountability becomes so much more powerful

105
00:03:33,310 --> 00:03:35,830
because we are a social species.

106
00:03:35,830 --> 00:03:38,580
So while accountability to yourself can be useful

107
00:03:38,580 --> 00:03:40,720
when somebody else is holding your feet to the fire,

108
00:03:40,719 --> 00:03:42,748
that is so, so much better.

109
00:03:42,750 --> 00:03:45,500
Now, level two is the most casual one in this category.

110
00:03:45,500 --> 00:03:48,140
And it involves introducing an accountability partner

111
00:03:48,139 --> 00:03:48,972
into the mix.

112
00:03:48,973 --> 00:03:51,550
An accountability partner is somebody who likes you

113
00:03:51,550 --> 00:03:53,779
or cares about you, cares about your goals

114
00:03:53,780 --> 00:03:56,449
and your progress, and will put in the effort

115
00:03:56,449 --> 00:03:58,169
to make sure that you're doing

116
00:03:58,169 --> 00:03:59,419
what you said you were going to do,

117
00:03:59,419 --> 00:04:01,189
who actually check up on you.

118
00:04:01,189 --> 00:04:03,568
This is a rare person than you might think.

119
00:04:03,569 --> 00:04:05,738
And a lot of people fall into a common pitfall

120
00:04:05,740 --> 00:04:07,860
where they go around telling all their friends and family

121
00:04:07,860 --> 00:04:09,130
about a goal that they have,

122
00:04:09,129 --> 00:04:11,669
assuming that these people will hold them accountable.

123
00:04:11,669 --> 00:04:12,609
But what actually happens

124
00:04:12,610 --> 00:04:14,269
is they end up sabotaging themselves

125
00:04:14,270 --> 00:04:16,470
due to something called a social reality.

126
00:04:16,470 --> 00:04:18,369
This is when you feel like you have actually

127
00:04:18,370 --> 00:04:19,910
made some progress on your goal,

128
00:04:19,910 --> 00:04:22,240
due to the praise you receive from other people

129
00:04:22,240 --> 00:04:23,619
after you tell them about it.

130
00:04:23,620 --> 00:04:24,797
You feel like something has happened

131
00:04:24,797 --> 00:04:27,340
but in reality, no progress has been made.

132
00:04:27,339 --> 00:04:28,259
And research has found

133
00:04:28,259 --> 00:04:29,638
that people who talk about their goals

134
00:04:29,639 --> 00:04:31,989
tend to practice less and quit more often.

135
00:04:31,990 --> 00:04:33,970
So in general, you shouldn't go around

136
00:04:33,970 --> 00:04:34,840
talking about your goals

137
00:04:34,839 --> 00:04:37,419
because you want to avoid these social realities.

138
00:04:37,420 --> 00:04:39,609
But the caveat here is that if you can find somebody

139
00:04:39,610 --> 00:04:42,029
who will actually act as an accountability partner,

140
00:04:42,029 --> 00:04:43,059
telling them about your goal

141
00:04:43,060 --> 00:04:45,750
and having them hold you accountable can be very powerful.

142
00:04:45,750 --> 00:04:46,909
And I have an example here.

143
00:04:46,910 --> 00:04:48,180
So a few years ago I decided

144
00:04:48,180 --> 00:04:49,890
that I wanted to read more non-fiction.

145
00:04:49,889 --> 00:04:51,839
So I went to my best friend Martin, and I said,

146
00:04:51,839 --> 00:04:55,149
I'm going to read 25 pages of nonfiction every single day

147
00:04:55,149 --> 00:04:56,409
for the next three months.

148
00:04:56,410 --> 00:04:59,689
And if I skip even one day, I'm gonna give you $100,

149
00:04:59,689 --> 00:05:01,379
so please hold me accountable.

150
00:05:01,379 --> 00:05:02,838
And to help him keep me accountable

151
00:05:02,839 --> 00:05:04,579
I also created a spreadsheet for him.

152
00:05:04,579 --> 00:05:07,038
That's right, it is spreadsheet time once again.

153
00:05:07,040 --> 00:05:09,249
So I created a sheet where I would record how many pages

154
00:05:09,250 --> 00:05:10,879
I read each day and from what book,

155
00:05:10,879 --> 00:05:12,649
and I gave him access to that sheet.

156
00:05:12,649 --> 00:05:15,019
And Martin was actually a great accountability partner.

157
00:05:15,019 --> 00:05:16,428
There were some days where I wouldn't do my reading

158
00:05:16,430 --> 00:05:17,940
until like 11:00 p.m. at night,

159
00:05:17,939 --> 00:05:19,799
and on those days I remember him texting me

160
00:05:19,800 --> 00:05:20,633
or coming up and saying,

161
00:05:20,632 --> 00:05:22,829
"Hey, why haven't you done your reading yet?"

162
00:05:22,829 --> 00:05:25,239
And Martin was a particularly good accountability partner

163
00:05:25,240 --> 00:05:27,780
because he didn't really want the $100.

164
00:05:27,779 --> 00:05:30,308
- I don't want your filthy failure money, Tom.

165
00:05:30,310 --> 00:05:33,350
- So Martin is definitely a great accountability partner.

166
00:05:33,350 --> 00:05:35,390
And if you have a Martin in your life,

167
00:05:35,389 --> 00:05:37,009
lean on them the next time you're having trouble

168
00:05:37,009 --> 00:05:38,779
sticking to a goal on your own,

169
00:05:38,779 --> 00:05:40,708
that accountability they bring to the table

170
00:05:40,709 --> 00:05:43,168
is like a force multiplier for your self-discipline.

171
00:05:43,170 --> 00:05:44,619
Now, if you don't have somebody in your life

172
00:05:44,620 --> 00:05:46,519
who can act as a great accountability partner,

173
00:05:46,519 --> 00:05:48,019
you can always move up to level three,

174
00:05:48,019 --> 00:05:50,329
which is to hire a coach or a teacher.

175
00:05:50,329 --> 00:05:51,849
Coaches and teachers are essentially

176
00:05:51,850 --> 00:05:53,729
professional accountability partners

177
00:05:53,730 --> 00:05:55,899
and they bring some additional benefits to the table.

178
00:05:55,899 --> 00:05:58,338
A great coach is somebody has the expertise

179
00:05:58,339 --> 00:05:59,478
in the thing that you wanna learn.

180
00:05:59,480 --> 00:06:01,020
They can either do it themselves now,

181
00:06:01,019 --> 00:06:02,829
they're at the level you're trying to get to,

182
00:06:02,829 --> 00:06:04,958
or they were at that level one point in their lives

183
00:06:04,959 --> 00:06:06,809
and have the experience they can lean on

184
00:06:06,810 --> 00:06:08,530
to teach you to get there.

185
00:06:08,529 --> 00:06:11,029
But they also have experience with teaching.

186
00:06:11,029 --> 00:06:13,969
And this is really a true skill area unto its own.

187
00:06:13,970 --> 00:06:15,500
Some people are experts,

188
00:06:15,500 --> 00:06:18,089
but they fall victim to what's called the expert paradox,

189
00:06:18,089 --> 00:06:20,528
where they are so good at what they do

190
00:06:20,529 --> 00:06:22,329
that it's become like breathing to them.

191
00:06:22,329 --> 00:06:24,529
It is second nature, it's completely unconscious.

192
00:06:24,529 --> 00:06:25,362
And because of that,

193
00:06:25,362 --> 00:06:26,769
they don't know how to break it down

194
00:06:26,769 --> 00:06:29,188
into the manageable beginner chunks

195
00:06:29,189 --> 00:06:31,278
that somebody at your level needs

196
00:06:31,279 --> 00:06:33,379
to actually understand and make progress.

197
00:06:33,379 --> 00:06:36,079
So a great coach is somebody with both the expertise

198
00:06:36,079 --> 00:06:37,639
and the teaching ability,

199
00:06:37,639 --> 00:06:40,679
but also someone who is invested in your success.

200
00:06:40,680 --> 00:06:42,650
And this is what separates a great coach

201
00:06:42,649 --> 00:06:43,818
from a mere good one.

202
00:06:43,819 --> 00:06:46,678
Somebody who actually cares about you making progress.

203
00:06:46,680 --> 00:06:47,920
Now there are actually platforms out there

204
00:06:47,920 --> 00:06:48,900
where you can hire coaches

205
00:06:48,899 --> 00:06:50,749
for a surprisingly affordable rates.

206
00:06:50,750 --> 00:06:52,890
Coach.me is the one that I can think of.

207
00:06:52,889 --> 00:06:55,268
But great coaches in my experience

208
00:06:55,269 --> 00:06:56,908
often cost a good amount of money.

209
00:06:56,910 --> 00:06:58,640
So this is something where you may wanna look for

210
00:06:58,639 --> 00:07:01,329
an accountability partner first and then move up to coaching

211
00:07:01,329 --> 00:07:03,378
when you have the means or when you're very serious

212
00:07:03,379 --> 00:07:04,588
about making progress.

213
00:07:04,589 --> 00:07:07,059
Now, level four is a whole different ball game

214
00:07:07,060 --> 00:07:08,550
than levels two and three,

215
00:07:08,550 --> 00:07:10,869
because with accountability partners and coaches,

216
00:07:10,870 --> 00:07:12,640
these people are exerting effort

217
00:07:12,639 --> 00:07:14,699
to give you the accountability you need

218
00:07:14,699 --> 00:07:16,199
for your personal goals.

219
00:07:16,199 --> 00:07:18,989
Level four involves joining a team or a group

220
00:07:18,990 --> 00:07:21,329
or an organization so that your personal goal

221
00:07:21,329 --> 00:07:23,688
becomes aligned with a common goal.

222
00:07:23,689 --> 00:07:25,929
And in doing so, you now have other people

223
00:07:25,930 --> 00:07:28,260
who are relying on you to do your part,

224
00:07:28,259 --> 00:07:31,759
and this makes the accountability so much more powerful.

225
00:07:31,759 --> 00:07:32,609
Now, when it comes to teams,

226
00:07:32,610 --> 00:07:35,400
I see two different types in this dynamic here.

227
00:07:35,399 --> 00:07:37,219
First, there are groups of people

228
00:07:37,220 --> 00:07:40,700
who have come together to all pursue their personal goals

229
00:07:40,699 --> 00:07:41,679
in a group setting.

230
00:07:41,680 --> 00:07:43,069
Think about like a casual,

231
00:07:43,069 --> 00:07:45,419
but fast cycling ride on the weekend.

232
00:07:45,420 --> 00:07:47,040
There are a lot of these on meetup here in Denver,

233
00:07:47,040 --> 00:07:49,200
and I've actually participated in one in the past.

234
00:07:49,199 --> 00:07:51,538
Some of these are what are called drop rides,

235
00:07:51,540 --> 00:07:54,200
where if the pack is going faster than you,

236
00:07:54,199 --> 00:07:55,509
you are going to get dropped.

237
00:07:55,509 --> 00:07:56,928
Meaning they're not gonna stop up the road

238
00:07:56,930 --> 00:07:58,890
and wait for you and let you rejoin the pack,

239
00:07:58,889 --> 00:08:01,089
you get dropped, you just need to ride home.

240
00:08:01,089 --> 00:08:04,508
In this instance, you are not really contributing

241
00:08:04,509 --> 00:08:07,469
to a common goal so much as you are in a pack of people

242
00:08:07,470 --> 00:08:09,470
who are all riding for the camaraderie,

243
00:08:09,470 --> 00:08:10,929
but it's still powerful.

244
00:08:10,930 --> 00:08:12,490
If you see a pack pulling ahead of you

245
00:08:12,490 --> 00:08:13,860
and you're falling behind,

246
00:08:13,860 --> 00:08:15,960
well, there's not a whole lot more in this world

247
00:08:15,959 --> 00:08:18,849
that's gonna make you motivated to really step on the gas

248
00:08:18,850 --> 00:08:21,269
and try to keep up with that pack.

249
00:08:21,269 --> 00:08:24,009
But the one thing that is more powerful than that,

250
00:08:24,009 --> 00:08:26,138
is being part of a team where your input

251
00:08:26,139 --> 00:08:29,319
is literally needed for everyone to meet their goal.

252
00:08:29,319 --> 00:08:30,758
Think of a relay race,

253
00:08:30,759 --> 00:08:33,629
if you never make it to the area where the next person

254
00:08:33,629 --> 00:08:36,079
is waiting for you to pass the baton, they can't run.

255
00:08:36,080 --> 00:08:36,930
And if you're slow,

256
00:08:36,929 --> 00:08:38,088
they're never gonna be able to catch up

257
00:08:38,090 --> 00:08:39,380
with their competitor.

258
00:08:39,379 --> 00:08:41,339
So whatever your personal goal is,

259
00:08:41,340 --> 00:08:44,219
if you can find a team or an organization that you can join,

260
00:08:44,220 --> 00:08:46,809
where your contributions will be needed,

261
00:08:46,809 --> 00:08:49,088
but you can also develop your own abilities,

262
00:08:49,090 --> 00:08:50,150
that's powerful.

263
00:08:50,149 --> 00:08:52,658
The only thing more powerful is level five.

264
00:08:52,659 --> 00:08:55,109
And before I reveal what this level is,

265
00:08:55,110 --> 00:08:57,909
I do wanna say that this is not the domain of life facts.

266
00:08:57,909 --> 00:09:00,359
This is not a level to go to if you want to add

267
00:09:00,360 --> 00:09:02,449
some self-discipline into your own life,

268
00:09:02,450 --> 00:09:04,740
but it is a level that has to be included in this model,

269
00:09:04,740 --> 00:09:06,669
otherwise it would be incomplete.

270
00:09:06,669 --> 00:09:08,558
Level five is leadership.

271
00:09:08,559 --> 00:09:10,309
Now, instead of being part of a team

272
00:09:10,309 --> 00:09:12,739
and having people rely on you just to do your part,

273
00:09:12,740 --> 00:09:14,580
now you've stepped up into a leadership role

274
00:09:14,580 --> 00:09:17,459
and everyone is relying on you to guide them as well.

275
00:09:17,460 --> 00:09:18,293
When you're a leader,

276
00:09:18,293 --> 00:09:20,729
the accountability is at its highest point,

277
00:09:20,730 --> 00:09:23,410
but also the responsibility and the consequences

278
00:09:23,409 --> 00:09:25,449
for failure are as well.

279
00:09:25,450 --> 00:09:27,539
So those are the five levels of self-discipline

280
00:09:27,539 --> 00:09:29,448
as they pertain it to accountability.

281
00:09:29,450 --> 00:09:30,1000
Accountability to yourself,

282
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:33,319
to partners, to coaches and teachers,

283
00:09:33,320 --> 00:09:35,320
to teams, and to people beneath you

284
00:09:35,320 --> 00:09:37,170
when you were in leadership positions.

285
00:09:37,169 --> 00:09:39,078
Now with accountability partners in general,

286
00:09:39,080 --> 00:09:40,570
it can be tough to find good ones

287
00:09:40,570 --> 00:09:43,090
who will actually stick with you and hold you accountable.

